SKILL|research-paper-writing|"Write ML papers for NeurIPS/ICML/ICLR: design→submit."
STEP|1|**Starting a new research paper** from an existing codebase or idea
STEP|2|**Designing and running experiments** to support paper claims
STEP|3|**Writing or revising** any section of a research paper
STEP|4|**Preparing for submission** to a specific conference or workshop
STEP|5|**Responding to reviews** with additional experiments or revisions
STEP|6|**Converting** a paper between conference formats
STEP|7|**Writing non-empirical papers** — theory, survey, benchmark, or position papers (see [Paper Types Beyond Empirical ML](#paper-types-beyond-empirical-ml))
STEP|8|**Designing human evaluations** for NLP, HCI, or alignment research
STEP|9|**Preparing post-acceptance deliverables** — posters, talks, code releases
STEP|10|**Be proactive.** Deliver complete drafts, not questions. Scientists are busy — produce something concrete they can react to, then iterate.
STEP|11|**Never hallucinate citations.** AI-generated citations have ~40% error rate. Always fetch programmatically. Mark unverifiable citations as `[CITATION NEEDED]`.
STEP|12|**Paper is a story, not a collection of experiments.** Every paper needs one clear contribution stated in a single sentence. If you can't do that, the paper isn't ready.
STEP|13|**Experiments serve claims.** Every experiment must explicitly state which claim it supports. Never run experiments that don't connect to the paper's narrative.
STEP|14|**Commit early, commit often.** Every completed experiment batch, every paper draft update — commit with descriptive messages. Git log is the experiment history.
STEP|15|Default: Be proactive. Draft first, ask with the draft.**
STEP|16|Block for input only when**: target venue unclear, multiple contradictory framings, results seem incomplete, explicit request to review first.
STEP|17|Goal**: Establish the workspace, understand existing work, identify the contribution.
STEP|18|`README.md` — project overview and claims
STEP|19|`results/`, `outputs/`, `experiments/` — existing findings
STEP|20|`configs/` — experimental settings
STEP|21|`.bib` files — existing citations
STEP|22|Draft documents or notes
STEP|23|Git discipline**: Every completed experiment batch gets committed with a descriptive message. Example:
STEP|24|**The What**: What is the single thing this paper contributes?
STEP|25|**The Why**: What evidence supports it?
STEP|26|**The So What**: Why should readers care?
STEP|27|[ ] Define one-sentence contribution
STEP|28|[ ] Literature review (related work + baselines)
STEP|29|[ ] Design core experiments
STEP|30|[ ] Run experiments
STEP|31|[ ] Analyze results
STEP|32|[ ] Write first draft
STEP|33|[ ] Self-review (simulate reviewers)
STEP|34|[ ] Revise based on review
STEP|35|[ ] Submission prep
STEP|36|[ ] API costs: (model price per token) × (estimated tokens per run) × (number of runs)
STEP|37|[ ] GPU hours: (time per experiment) × (number of experiments) × (number of seeds)
STEP|38|[ ] Human evaluation costs: (annotators) × (hours) × (hourly rate)
STEP|39|[ ] Total budget ceiling and contingency (add 30-50% for reruns)
STEP|40|When budget is tight**: Run pilot experiments (1-2 seeds, subset of tasks) before committing to full sweeps. Use cheaper models for debugging pipelines, then switch to target models for final runs.
STEP|41|Section ownership**: Assign each section to one primary author. Others comment but don't edit directly. Prevents merge conflicts and style inconsistency.
STEP|42|[ ] Agree on section ownership (who writes what)
STEP|43|[ ] Set up shared workspace (Overleaf or git repo)
STEP|44|[ ] Establish notation conventions (before anyone writes)
STEP|45|[ ] Schedule internal review rounds (not just at the end)
STEP|46|[ ] Designate one person for final formatting pass
STEP|47|[ ] Agree on figure style (colors, fonts, sizes) before creating figures
STEP|48|LaTeX conventions to agree on early**:
STEP|49|`\method{}` macro for consistent method naming
STEP|50|Citation style: `\citet{}` vs `\citep{}` usage
STEP|51|Math notation: lowercase bold for vectors, uppercase bold for matrices, etc.
STEP|52|British vs American spelling
STEP|53|Goal**: Find related work, identify baselines, gather citations.
STEP|54|Load the `arxiv` skill** for structured paper discovery: `skill_view("arxiv")`. It provides arXiv REST API search, Semantic Scholar citation graphs, author profiles, and BibTeX generation.
STEP|55|"[main technique] + [application domain]"
STEP|56|"[baseline method] comparison"
STEP|57|"[problem name] state-of-the-art"
STEP|58|Author names from existing citations
STEP|59|Recommended**: Install **Exa MCP** for real-time academic search:
STEP|60|When to stop**: If a round returns >80% papers already in your collection, the search is saturated. Typically 2-3 rounds suffice. For survey papers, expect 4-5 rounds.
STEP|61|For agent-based workflows**: Delegate each round's queries in parallel via `delegate_task`. Collect results, deduplicate, then generate the next round's queries from the combined learnings.
STEP|62|NEVER generate BibTeX from memory. ALWAYS fetch programmatically.**
STEP|63|SEARCH → Query Semantic Scholar or Exa MCP with specific keywords
STEP|64|VERIFY → Confirm paper exists in 2+ sources (Semantic Scholar + arXiv/CrossRef)
STEP|65|RETRIEVE → Get BibTeX via DOI content negotiation (programmatically, not from memory)
STEP|66|VALIDATE → Confirm the claim you're citing actually appears in the paper
STEP|67|ADD → Add verified BibTeX to bibliography
STEP|68|Always tell the scientist**: "I've marked [X] citations as placeholders that need verification."
STEP|69|Good**: "One line of work uses X's assumption [refs] whereas we use Y's assumption because..."
STEP|70|Bad**: "Smith et al. introduced X. Jones et al. introduced Y. We combine both."
STEP|71|Goal**: Design experiments that directly support paper claims. Every experiment must answer a specific question.
STEP|72|Rule**: If an experiment doesn't map to a claim, don't run it.
STEP|73|**Naive baseline**: Simplest possible approach
STEP|74|**Strong baseline**: Best known existing method
STEP|75|**Ablation baselines**: Your method minus one component
STEP|76|**Compute-matched baselines**: Same compute budget, different allocation
STEP|77|**Metrics**: What you're measuring, direction symbols (higher/lower better)
STEP|78|**Aggregation**: How results are combined across runs/tasks
STEP|79|**Statistical tests**: What tests will establish significance
STEP|80|**Sample sizes**: How many runs/problems/tasks
STEP|81|Incremental saving** — save results after each step for crash recovery:
STEP|82|Artifact preservation** — save all intermediate outputs:
STEP|83|Separation of concerns** — keep generation, evaluation, and visualization separate:
STEP|84|When human evaluation is needed:**
STEP|85|Automated metrics don't capture what you care about (fluency, helpfulness, safety)
STEP|86|Your contribution is about human-facing qualities (readability, preference, trust)
STEP|87|Reviewers at NLP venues (ACL, EMNLP) expect it for generation tasks
STEP|88|Key design decisions:**
STEP|89|Annotation guideline checklist:**
STEP|90|[ ] Clear task description with examples (good AND bad)
STEP|91|[ ] Decision criteria for ambiguous cases
STEP|92|[ ] At least 2 worked examples per category
STEP|93|[ ] Attention checks / gold standard items (10-15% of total)
STEP|94|[ ] Qualification task or screening round
STEP|95|[ ] Estimated time per item and fair compensation (>= local minimum wage)
STEP|96|[ ] IRB/ethics review if required by your institution
STEP|97|Reporting requirements** (reviewers check all of these):
STEP|98|Number of annotators and their qualifications
STEP|99|Inter-annotator agreement with specific metric and value
STEP|100|Compensation details (amount, estimated hourly rate)
STEP|101|Annotation interface description or screenshot (appendix)
STEP|102|Total annotation time
STEP|103|Goal**: Run experiments reliably, monitor progress, recover from failures.
STEP|104|Parallel execution**: Run independent experiments simultaneously, but be aware of API rate limits. 4+ concurrent experiments on the same API will slow each down.
STEP|105|Check if process is still running: ps aux \| grep <pattern>
STEP|106|Read last 30 lines of log: tail -30 <logfile>
STEP|107|Check for completed results: ls <result_dir>
STEP|108|If results exist, read and report: cat <result_file>
STEP|109|If all done, commit: git add -A && git commit -m "<descriptive message>" && git push
STEP|110|Report in structured format (tables with key metrics)
STEP|111|Answer the key analytical question for this experiment
STEP|112|Silent mode**: If nothing has changed since the last check, respond with `[SILENT]` to suppress notification to the user. Only report when there's news.
STEP|113|Key**: Scripts should always check for existing results and skip completed work. This makes re-runs safe and efficient.
STEP|114|Why a journal, not just git?** Git tracks file changes. The journal tracks the reasoning: why you tried X, what you learned, and what that implies for the next experiment. When writing the paper, this
STEP|115|Selecting the best path**: When the journal shows a branching tree (exp_001 → exp_002a, exp_002b, exp_003), identify the path that best supports the paper's claims. Document dead-end branches in the a
STEP|116|Snapshot code per experiment**: Copy the experiment script after each run:
STEP|117|Goal**: Extract findings, compute statistics, identify the story.
STEP|118|Load all result files from a batch
STEP|119|Compute per-task and aggregate metrics
STEP|120|Generate summary tables
STEP|121|**Error bars**: Standard deviation or standard error, specify which
STEP|122|**Confidence intervals**: 95% CI for key results
STEP|123|**Pairwise tests**: McNemar's test for comparing two methods
STEP|124|**Effect sizes**: Cohen's d or h for practical significance
STEP|125|**What is the main finding?** State it in one sentence.
STEP|126|**What surprised you?** Unexpected results often make the best papers.
STEP|127|**What failed?** Failed experiments can be the most informative. Honest reporting of failures strengthens the paper.
STEP|128|**What follow-up experiments are needed?** Results often raise new questions.
STEP|129|How to write a negative results paper:**
STEP|130|Lead with what the community believes and why it matters to test it
STEP|131|Describe your rigorous methodology (must be airtight — reviewers will scrutinize harder)
STEP|132|Present the null result clearly with statistical evidence
STEP|133|Analyze **why** the expected result didn't materialize
STEP|134|Discuss implications for the field
STEP|135|Venues that explicitly welcome negative results**: NeurIPS (Datasets & Benchmarks track), TMLR, ML Reproducibility Challenge, workshops at major conferences. Some workshops specifically call for negat
STEP|136|Figures**:
STEP|137|Use vector graphics (PDF) for all plots: `plt.savefig('fig.pdf')`
STEP|138|Colorblind-safe palettes (Okabe-Ito or Paul Tol)
STEP|139|Self-contained captions — reader should understand without main text
STEP|140|No title inside figure — the caption serves this function
STEP|141|Tables**:
STEP|142|Use `booktabs` LaTeX package
STEP|143|Bold best value per metric
STEP|144|Include direction symbols (higher/lower better)
STEP|145|Consistent decimal precision
STEP|146|Create `experiment_log.md`** with the following structure:
STEP|147|**Claim tested**: [Which paper claim this supports]
STEP|148|**Setup**: [Model, dataset, config, number of runs]
STEP|149|**Key result**: [One sentence with the number]
STEP|150|**Result files**: results/exp1/final_info.json
STEP|151|**Figures generated**: figures/exp1_comparison.pdf
STEP|152|**Surprising findings**: [Anything unexpected]
STEP|153|[What was tried, why it failed, what it tells us]
STEP|154|[Anything the results raised that the paper should address]
STEP|155|Why this matters**: When drafting, the agent (or a delegated sub-agent) can load `experiment_log.md` alongside the LaTeX template and produce a first draft grounded in actual results. Without this bri
STEP|156|Git discipline**: Commit this log alongside the results it describes.
STEP|157|Core insight**: Autoreason's value depends on the gap between a model's generation capability and its self-evaluation capability.
STEP|158|**Critic** → finds problems in incumbent A (no fixes)
STEP|159|**Author B** → revises A based on critique
STEP|160|**Synthesizer** → merges A and B (randomized labels)
STEP|161|**Judge Panel** → 3 blind CoT judges rank A, B, AB via Borda count
STEP|162|**Convergence** → A wins k=2 consecutive passes → done
STEP|163|Key parameters:**
STEP|164|k=2 convergence (k=1 premature, k=3 too expensive, no quality gain)
STEP|165|CoT judges always (3x faster convergence)
STEP|166|Temperature 0.8 authors, 0.3 judges
STEP|167|Conservative tiebreak: incumbent wins ties
STEP|168|Every role is a fresh agent with no shared context
STEP|169|**Provide ground truth to the critic**: actual experimental data, result JSONs, statistical outputs. Without this, models hallucinate fabricated ablation studies and fake confidence intervals.
STEP|170|**Use 3 working judges minimum**: A broken judge parser doesn't add noise — it prevents equilibrium entirely.
STEP|171|**Scope constrain the revision**: "Address these specific weaknesses" not "improve the paper."
STEP|172|Goal**: Write a complete, publication-ready paper.
STEP|173|What to load into context per drafting task:**
STEP|174|Principles:**
STEP|175|**`experiment_log.md` is the primary context bridge** — it summarizes everything needed for writing without loading raw data files (see Step 4.6)
STEP|176|**Load one section's context at a time** when delegating. A sub-agent drafting Methods doesn't need the literature review notes.
STEP|177|**Summarize, don't include raw files.** For a 200-line result JSON, load a 10-line summary table. For a 50-page related paper, load the 5-sentence abstract + your 2-line note about its relevance.
STEP|178|**For very large projects**: Create a `context/` directory with pre-compressed summaries:
STEP|179|The single most critical insight**: Your paper is not a collection of experiments — it's a story with one clear contribution supported by evidence.
STEP|180|Three Pillars (must be crystal clear by end of introduction):**
STEP|181|If you cannot state your contribution in one sentence, you don't yet have a paper.**
STEP|182|For deeper dives into any of these, see:**
STEP|183|[references/writing-guide.md](references/writing-guide.md) — Full explanations with examples
STEP|184|[references/sources.md](references/sources.md) — Complete bibliography
STEP|185|The abstract
STEP|186|The introduction
STEP|187|The figures
STEP|188|Everything else combined
STEP|189|Why?** Most reviewers form judgments before reaching your methods. Readers encounter your paper as: title → abstract → introduction → figures → maybe the rest.
STEP|190|[ ] Step 1: Define the one-sentence contribution
STEP|191|[ ] Step 2: Draft Figure 1 (core idea or most compelling result)
STEP|192|[ ] Step 3: Draft abstract (5-sentence formula)
STEP|193|[ ] Step 4: Draft introduction (1-1.5 pages max)
STEP|194|[ ] Step 5: Draft methods
STEP|195|[ ] Step 6: Draft experiments & results
STEP|196|[ ] Step 7: Draft related work
STEP|197|[ ] Step 8: Draft conclusion & discussion
STEP|198|[ ] Step 9: Draft limitations (REQUIRED by all venues)
STEP|199|[ ] Step 10: Plan appendix (proofs, extra experiments, details)
STEP|200|[ ] Step 11: Complete paper checklist
STEP|201|[ ] Step 12: Final review
STEP|202|Pass 1 — Write + immediate refine per section:**
STEP|203|Pass 2 — Global refinement with full-paper context:**
STEP|204|Does it fit with the rest of the paper? Are there redundancies with other sections?
STEP|205|Is terminology consistent with Introduction and Methods?
STEP|206|Can anything be cut without weakening the message?
STEP|207|Does the narrative flow from the previous section and into the next?
STEP|208|[ ] No unenclosed math symbols ($ signs balanced)
STEP|209|[ ] Only reference figures/tables that exist (\ref matches \label)
STEP|210|[ ] No fabricated citations (\cite matches entries in .bib)
STEP|211|[ ] Every \begin{env} has matching \end{env} (especially figure, table, algorithm)
STEP|212|[ ] No HTML contamination (</end{figure}> instead of \end{figure})
STEP|213|[ ] No unescaped underscores outside math mode (use \_ in text)
STEP|214|[ ] No duplicate \label definitions
STEP|215|[ ] No duplicate section headers
STEP|216|[ ] Numbers in text match actual experimental results
STEP|217|[ ] All figures have captions and labels
STEP|218|[ ] No overly long lines that cause overfull hbox warnings
STEP|219|Good titles**:
STEP|220|State the contribution or finding: "Autoreason: When Iterative LLM Refinement Works and Why It Fails"
STEP|221|Highlight a surprising result: "Scaling Data-Constrained Language Models" (implies you can)
STEP|222|Name the method + what it does: "DPO: Direct Preference Optimization of Language Models"
STEP|223|Bad titles**:
STEP|224|Too generic: "An Approach to Improving Language Model Outputs"
STEP|225|Too long: anything over ~15 words
STEP|226|Jargon-only: "Asymptotic Convergence of Iterative Stochastic Policy Refinement" (who is this for?)
STEP|227|Rules**:
STEP|228|Include your method name if you have one (for citability)
STEP|229|Include 1-2 keywords reviewers will search for
STEP|230|Avoid colons unless both halves carry meaning
STEP|231|Test: would a reviewer know the domain and contribution from the title alone?
STEP|232|What you achieved: "We introduce...", "We prove...", "We demonstrate..."
STEP|233|Why this is hard and important
STEP|234|How you do it (with specialist keywords for discoverability)
STEP|235|What evidence you have
STEP|236|Your most remarkable number/result
STEP|237|Delete** generic openings like "Large language models have achieved remarkable success..."
STEP|238|Rules**: Figure 1 must be understandable without reading any text. The caption alone should communicate the core idea. Use color purposefully — don't just decorate.
STEP|239|Clear problem statement
STEP|240|Brief approach overview
STEP|241|2-4 bullet contribution list (max 1-2 lines each in two-column format)
STEP|242|Methods should start by page 2-3
STEP|243|Conceptual outline or pseudocode
STEP|244|All hyperparameters listed
STEP|245|Architectural details sufficient for reproduction
STEP|246|Present final design decisions; ablations go in experiments
STEP|247|**What claim it supports**
STEP|248|How it connects to main contribution
STEP|249|What to observe: "the blue line shows X, which demonstrates Y"
STEP|250|Error bars with methodology (std dev vs std error)
STEP|251|Hyperparameter search ranges
STEP|252|Compute infrastructure (GPU type, total hours)
STEP|253|Seed-setting methods
STEP|254|Reviewers are instructed not to penalize honest limitation acknowledgment
STEP|255|Pre-empt criticisms by identifying weaknesses first
STEP|256|Explain why limitations don't undermine core claims
STEP|257|Conclusion** (required, 0.5-1 page):
STEP|258|Restate the contribution in one sentence (different wording from abstract)
STEP|259|Summarize key findings (2-3 sentences, not a list)
STEP|260|Implications: what does this mean for the field?
STEP|261|Future work: 2-3 concrete next steps (not vague "we leave X for future work")
STEP|262|Discussion** (optional, sometimes combined with conclusion):
STEP|263|Broader implications beyond immediate results
STEP|264|Connections to other subfields
STEP|265|Honest assessment of when the method does and doesn't work
STEP|266|Practical deployment considerations
STEP|267|Do NOT** introduce new results or claims in the conclusion.
STEP|268|Rules**:
STEP|269|The main paper must be self-contained — reviewers are not required to read appendices
STEP|270|Never put critical evidence only in the appendix
STEP|271|Cross-reference: "Full results in Table 5 (Appendix B)" not just "see appendix"
STEP|272|Use `\appendix` command, then `\section{A: Proofs}` etc.
STEP|273|Do NOT**: reduce font size, change margins, remove required sections (limitations, broader impact), or use `\small`/`\footnotesize` for main text.
STEP|274|What to include:**
STEP|275|Writing the statement:**
STEP|276|Common mistakes:**
STEP|277|Writing "we foresee no negative impacts" (almost never true — reviewers distrust this)
STEP|278|Being vague: "this could be misused" without specifying how
STEP|279|Ignoring compute costs for large-scale work
STEP|280|Forgetting to disclose LLM use at venues that require it
STEP|281|Compute carbon footprint** (for training-heavy papers):
STEP|282|Datasheets for Datasets** (Gebru et al., 2021) — include in appendix:
STEP|283|Motivation: Why was this dataset created? What task does it support?
STEP|284|Composition: What are the instances? How many? What data types?
STEP|285|Collection: How was data collected? What was the source?
STEP|286|Preprocessing: What cleaning/filtering was applied?
STEP|287|Distribution: How is the dataset distributed? Under what license?
STEP|288|Maintenance: Who maintains it? How to report issues?
STEP|289|Ethical considerations: Contains personal data? Consent obtained?
STEP|290|Model Cards** (Mitchell et al., 2019) — include in appendix for model releases:
STEP|291|Model details: Architecture, training data, training procedure
STEP|292|Intended use: Primary use cases, out-of-scope uses
STEP|293|Metrics: Evaluation metrics and results on benchmarks
STEP|294|Ethical considerations: Known biases, fairness evaluations
STEP|295|Limitations: Known failure modes, domains where model underperforms
STEP|296|Sentence-level clarity (Gopen & Swan's 7 Principles):**
STEP|297|Word choice (Lipton, Steinhardt):**
STEP|298|Be specific: "accuracy" not "performance"
STEP|299|Eliminate hedging: drop "may" unless genuinely uncertain
STEP|300|Consistent terminology throughout
STEP|301|Avoid incremental vocabulary: "develop", not "combine"
STEP|302|Full writing guide with examples**: See [references/writing-guide.md](references/writing-guide.md)
STEP|303|Always copy the entire template directory first, then write within it.**
