STEP|311|Step 2: Verify Template Compiles First**
STEP|312|Step 3: Keep Template Content as Reference**
STEP|313|Step 4: Replace Content Section by Section**
STEP|314|Step 5: Use Template Macros**
STEP|315|Universal**: Double-blind, references don't count, appendices unlimited, LaTeX required.
STEP|316|Tables** — use `booktabs` for professional formatting:
STEP|317|Bold best value per metric
STEP|318|Include direction symbols ($\uparrow$ higher better, $\downarrow$ lower better)
STEP|319|Right-align numerical columns
STEP|320|Consistent decimal precision
STEP|321|Figures**:
STEP|322|**Vector graphics** (PDF, EPS) for all plots and diagrams — `plt.savefig('fig.pdf')`
STEP|323|**Raster** (PNG 600 DPI) only for photographs
STEP|324|**Colorblind-safe palettes** (Okabe-Ito or Paul Tol)
STEP|325|Verify **grayscale readability** (8% of men have color vision deficiency)
STEP|326|**No title inside figure** — the caption serves this function
STEP|327|**Self-contained captions** — reader should understand without main text
STEP|328|Notes:**
STEP|329|`microtype` is the single highest-impact package for visual quality. It adjusts character spacing at a sub-pixel level. Always include it.
STEP|330|`siunitx` handles decimal alignment in tables via the `S` column type — eliminates manual spacing.
STEP|331|`cleveref` must be loaded **after** `hyperref`. Most conference .sty files load hyperref, so put cleveref last.
STEP|332|Check if the conference template already loads any of these (especially `algorithm`, `amsmath`, `graphicx`). Don't double-load.
STEP|333|Pipeline/Flow Diagram** (most common in ML papers):
STEP|334|Comparison/Matrix Diagram** (for showing method variants):
STEP|335|Iterative Loop Diagram** (for methods with feedback):
STEP|336|Standard figure sizes** (two-column format):
STEP|337|Single column: `figsize=(3.5, 2.5)` — fits in one column
STEP|338|Double column: `figsize=(7.0, 3.0)` — spans both columns
STEP|339|Square: `figsize=(3.5, 3.5)` — for heatmaps, confusion matrices
STEP|340|Goal**: Simulate the review process before submission. Catch weaknesses early.
STEP|341|Step 1: Generate N independent reviews** (N=3-5)
STEP|342|Soundness (are claims well-supported? are baselines fair and strong?)
STEP|343|Clarity (is the paper well-written? could an expert reproduce it?)
STEP|344|Significance (does this matter to the community?)
STEP|345|Originality (new insights, not just incremental combination?)
STEP|346|Step 2: Meta-review (Area Chair aggregation)**
STEP|347|Identify consensus strengths and weaknesses across reviewers
STEP|348|Resolve disagreements by examining the paper directly
STEP|349|Produce a meta-review that represents the aggregate judgment
STEP|350|Use AVERAGED numerical scores across all reviews
STEP|351|Step 3: Reflection loop** (optional, 2-3 rounds)
STEP|352|Model selection for reviewing**: Reviewing is best done with the strongest available model, even if you wrote the paper with a cheaper one. The reviewer model should be chosen independently from the w
STEP|353|Few-shot calibration**: If available, include 1-2 real published reviews from the target venue as examples. This dramatically improves score calibration. See [references/reviewer-guidelines.md](refere
STEP|354|Figure quality: Are plots readable? Labels legible? Colors distinguishable?
STEP|355|Figure-caption alignment: Does each caption accurately describe its figure?
STEP|356|Layout issues: Orphaned section headers, awkward page breaks, figures far from their references
STEP|357|Table formatting: Aligned columns, consistent decimal precision, bold for best results
STEP|358|Visual consistency: Same color scheme across all figures, consistent font sizes
STEP|359|Grayscale readability: Would the figures be understandable if printed in B&W?
STEP|360|Extract every factual claim from the paper (numbers, comparisons, trends)
STEP|361|For each claim, trace it to the specific experiment/result that supports it
STEP|362|Verify the number in the paper matches the actual result file
STEP|363|Flag any claim without a traceable source as [VERIFY]
STEP|364|Identify the specific section(s) affected
STEP|365|Draft the fix
STEP|366|Verify the fix doesn't break other claims
STEP|367|Update the paper
STEP|368|Re-check against the reviewer's concern
STEP|369|Format**: Point-by-point. For each reviewer concern:
STEP|370|Rules**:
STEP|371|Address every concern — reviewers notice if you skip one
STEP|372|Lead with the strongest responses
STEP|373|Be concise and direct — reviewers read dozens of rebuttals
STEP|374|Include new results if you ran experiments during the rebuttal period
STEP|375|Never be defensive or dismissive, even of weak criticisms
STEP|376|Use `latexdiff` to generate a marked-up PDF showing changes (see Professional LaTeX Tooling section)
STEP|377|Thank reviewers for specific, actionable feedback (not generic praise)
STEP|378|What NOT to do**: "We respectfully disagree" without evidence. "This is out of scope" without explanation. Ignoring a weakness by only responding to strengths.
STEP|379|Goal**: Final checks, formatting, and submission.
STEP|380|NeurIPS 16-item paper checklist
STEP|381|ICML broader impact + reproducibility
STEP|382|ICLR LLM disclosure policy
STEP|383|ACL mandatory limitations section
STEP|384|Universal pre-submission checklist
STEP|385|[ ] No author names or affiliations anywhere in the PDF
STEP|386|[ ] No acknowledgments section (add after acceptance)
STEP|387|[ ] Self-citations written in third person: "Smith et al. [1] showed..." not "We previously showed [1]..."
STEP|388|[ ] No GitHub/GitLab URLs pointing to your personal repos
STEP|389|[ ] Use Anonymous GitHub (https://anonymous.4open.science/) for code links
STEP|390|[ ] No institutional logos or identifiers in figures
STEP|391|[ ] No file metadata containing author names (check PDF properties)
STEP|392|[ ] No "our previous work" or "in our earlier paper" phrasing
STEP|393|[ ] Dataset names don't reveal institution (rename if needed)
STEP|394|[ ] Supplementary materials don't contain identifying information
STEP|395|Common mistakes**: Git commit messages visible in supplementary code, watermarked figures from institutional tools, acknowledgments left in from a previous draft, arXiv preprint posted before anonymit
STEP|396|[ ] Page limit respected (excluding references and appendix)
STEP|397|[ ] All figures are vector (PDF) or high-res raster (600 DPI PNG)
STEP|398|[ ] All figures readable in grayscale
STEP|399|[ ] All tables use booktabs
STEP|400|[ ] References compile correctly (no "?" in citations)
STEP|401|[ ] No overfull hboxes in critical areas
STEP|402|[ ] Appendix clearly labeled and separated
STEP|403|[ ] Required sections present (limitations, broader impact, etc.)
STEP|404|If compilation fails**: Parse the `.log` file for the first error. Common fixes:
STEP|405|"Undefined control sequence" → missing package or typo in command name
STEP|406|"Missing $ inserted" → math symbol outside math mode
STEP|407|"File not found" → wrong figure path or missing .sty file
STEP|408|"Citation undefined" → .bib entry missing or bibtex not run
STEP|409|After rejection**: Address reviewer concerns in the new version, but don't include a "changes" section or reference the previous submission (blind review).
STEP|410|[ ] De-anonymize: add author names, affiliations, email addresses
STEP|411|[ ] Add Acknowledgments section (funding, compute grants, helpful reviewers)
STEP|412|[ ] Add public code/data URL (real GitHub, not anonymous)
STEP|413|[ ] Address any mandatory revisions from meta-reviewer
STEP|414|[ ] Switch template to camera-ready mode (if applicable — e.g., AAAI \anon → \camera)
STEP|415|[ ] Add copyright notice if required by venue
STEP|416|[ ] Update any "anonymous" placeholders in text
STEP|417|[ ] Verify final PDF compiles cleanly
STEP|418|[ ] Check page limit for camera-ready (sometimes differs from submission)
STEP|419|[ ] Upload supplementary materials (code, data, appendix) to venue portal
STEP|420|Timing decision tree:**
STEP|421|arXiv category selection** (ML/AI papers):
STEP|422|List primary + 1-2 cross-listed categories.** More categories = more visibility, but only cross-list where genuinely relevant.
STEP|423|Versioning strategy:**
STEP|424|**v1**: Initial submission (matches conference submission)
STEP|425|**v2**: Post-acceptance with camera-ready corrections (add "accepted at [Venue]" to abstract)
STEP|426|Don't post v2 during the review period with changes that clearly respond to reviewer feedback
STEP|427|Repository structure:**
STEP|428|README template for research code:**
STEP|429|Pre-release checklist:**
STEP|430|[ ] Code runs from a clean clone (test on fresh machine or Docker)
STEP|431|[ ] All dependencies pinned to specific versions
STEP|432|[ ] No hardcoded absolute paths
STEP|433|[ ] No API keys, credentials, or personal data in repo
STEP|434|[ ] README covers setup, reproduction, and citation
STEP|435|[ ] LICENSE file present (MIT or Apache 2.0 for max reuse)
STEP|436|[ ] Results are reproducible within expected variance
STEP|437|[ ] .gitignore excludes data files, checkpoints, logs
STEP|438|Anonymous code for submission** (before acceptance):
STEP|439|Goal**: Maximize the impact of your accepted paper through presentation materials and community engagement.
STEP|440|Tools**: LaTeX (`beamerposter` package), PowerPoint/Keynote, Figma, Canva.
STEP|441|Production**: Order 2+ weeks before the conference. Fabric posters are lighter for travel. Many conferences now support virtual/digital posters too.
STEP|442|Slide design rules:**
STEP|443|One idea per slide
STEP|444|Minimize text — speak the details, don't project them
STEP|445|Animate key figures to build understanding step-by-step
STEP|446|Include a "takeaway" slide at the end (single sentence contribution)
STEP|447|Prepare backup slides for anticipated questions
STEP|448|**Twitter/X thread**: 5-8 tweets. Lead with the result, not the method. Include Figure 1 and key result figure.
STEP|449|**Blog post**: 800-1500 words. Written for ML practitioners, not reviewers. Skip formalism, emphasize intuition and practical implications.
STEP|450|**Project page**: HTML page with abstract, figures, demo, code link, BibTeX. Use GitHub Pages.
STEP|451|Timing**: Post within 1-2 days of paper appearing on proceedings or arXiv camera-ready.
STEP|452|When to target a workshop:**
STEP|453|Early-stage idea you want feedback on before a full paper
STEP|454|Negative result that doesn't justify 8+ pages
STEP|455|Position piece or opinion on a timely topic
STEP|456|Replication study or reproducibility report
STEP|457|Short paper strategy**: Pick ONE claim and support it thoroughly. Don't try to compress a long paper into 4 pages — write a different, more focused paper.
STEP|458|Structure**: Introduction → Preliminaries (definitions, notation) → Main Results (theorems) → Proof Sketches → Discussion → Full Proofs (appendix)
STEP|459|Key differences from empirical papers:**
STEP|460|Contribution is a theorem, bound, or impossibility result — not experimental numbers
STEP|461|Methods section replaced by "Preliminaries" and "Main Results"
STEP|462|Proofs are the evidence, not experiments (though empirical validation of theory is welcome)
STEP|463|Proof sketches in main text, full proofs in appendix is standard practice
STEP|464|Experimental section is optional but strengthens the paper if it validates theoretical predictions
STEP|465|Proof writing principles:**
STEP|466|State theorems formally with all assumptions explicit
STEP|467|Provide intuition before formal proof ("The key insight is...")
STEP|468|Proof sketches should convey the main idea in 0.5-1 page
STEP|469|Use `\begin{proof}...\end{proof}` environments
STEP|470|Number assumptions and reference them in theorems: "Under Assumptions 1-3, ..."
STEP|471|Structure**: Introduction → Taxonomy / Organization → Detailed Coverage → Open Problems → Conclusion
STEP|472|Key differences:**
STEP|473|Contribution is the organization, synthesis, and identification of open problems — not new methods
STEP|474|Must be comprehensive within scope (reviewers will check for missing references)
STEP|475|Requires a clear taxonomy or organizational framework
STEP|476|Value comes from connections between works that individual papers don't make
STEP|477|Best venues: TMLR (survey track), JMLR, Foundations and Trends in ML, ACM Computing Surveys
STEP|478|Structure**: Introduction → Task Definition → Dataset Construction → Baseline Evaluation → Analysis → Intended Use & Limitations
STEP|479|Key differences:**
STEP|480|Contribution is the benchmark itself — it must fill a genuine evaluation gap
STEP|481|Dataset documentation is mandatory, not optional (see Datasheets, Step 5.11)
STEP|482|Must demonstrate the benchmark is challenging (baselines don't saturate it)
STEP|483|Must demonstrate the benchmark measures what you claim it measures (construct validity)
STEP|484|Best venues: NeurIPS Datasets & Benchmarks track, ACL (resource papers), LREC-COLING
STEP|485|Structure**: Introduction → Background → Thesis / Argument → Supporting Evidence → Counterarguments → Implications
STEP|486|Key differences:**
STEP|487|Contribution is an argument, not a result
STEP|488|Must engage seriously with counterarguments
STEP|489|Evidence can be empirical, theoretical, or logical analysis
STEP|490|Best venues: ICML (position track), workshops, TMLR
STEP|491|This skill supersedes `ml-paper-writing`** — it contains all of ml-paper-writing's content plus the full experiment/analysis pipeline and autoreason methodology.
STEP|492|Experiment monitoring** (most common):
STEP|493|Parallel section drafting** (using delegation):
STEP|494|Citation verification** (using execute_code):
STEP|495|`memory` tool** — persist key decisions (bounded: ~2200 chars for MEMORY.md):
STEP|496|`todo` tool** — track granular progress:
STEP|497|Session startup protocol:**
STEP|498|todo("list") # Check current task list
STEP|499|memory("read") # Recall key decisions
STEP|500|terminal("git log --oneline -10") # Check recent commits
STEP|501|terminal("ps aux \| grep python") # Check running experiments
STEP|502|terminal("ls results/ \| tail -20") # Check for new results
STEP|503|Report status to user, ask for direction
STEP|504|[SILENT] protocol**: When nothing has changed since the last check, respond with exactly `[SILENT]`. This suppresses notification delivery to the user. Only report when there are genuine changes worth
STEP|505|Deadline tracking**:
STEP|506|When to notify the user** (via `send_message` or direct response):
STEP|507|Experiment batch completed (with results table)
STEP|508|Unexpected finding or failure requiring decision
STEP|509|Draft section ready for review
STEP|510|Deadline approaching with incomplete tasks
STEP|511|When NOT to notify:**
STEP|512|Experiment still running, no new results → `[SILENT]`
STEP|513|Routine monitoring with no changes → `[SILENT]`
STEP|514|Intermediate steps that don't need attention
STEP|515|Report format** — always include structured data:
STEP|516|Do NOT ask about** (be proactive, make a choice, flag it):
STEP|517|Word choice, section ordering
STEP|518|Which specific results to highlight
STEP|519|Citation completeness (draft with what you find, note gaps)
STEP|520|Scoring (NeurIPS 6-point scale):**
STEP|521|6: Strong Accept — groundbreaking, flawless
STEP|522|5: Accept — technically solid, high impact
STEP|523|4: Borderline Accept — solid, limited evaluation
STEP|524|3: Borderline Reject — weaknesses outweigh
STEP|525|2: Reject — technical flaws
STEP|526|1: Strong Reject — known results or ethics issues
STEP|527|Writing Philosophy:**
STEP|528|[Neel Nanda: How to Write ML Papers](https://www.alignmentforum.org/posts/eJGptPbbFPZGLpjsp/highly-opinionated-advice-on-how-to-write-ml-papers)
STEP|529|[Sebastian Farquhar: How to Write ML Papers](https://sebastianfarquhar.com/on-research/2024/11/04/how_to_write_ml_papers/)
STEP|530|[Gopen & Swan: Science of Scientific Writing](https://cseweb.ucsd.edu/~swanson/papers/science-of-writing.pdf)
STEP|531|[Lipton: Heuristics for Scientific Writing](https://www.approximatelycorrect.com/2018/01/29/heuristics-technical-scientific-writing-machine-learning-perspective/)
STEP|532|[Perez: Easy Paper Writing Tips](https://ethanperez.net/easy-paper-writing-tips/)
STEP|533|APIs:** [Semantic Scholar](https://api.semanticscholar.org/api-docs/) \| [CrossRef](https://www.crossref.org/documentation/retrieve-metadata/rest-api/) \| [arXiv](https://info.arxiv.org/help/api/basic
STEP|534|Venues:** [NeurIPS](https://neurips.cc/Conferences/2025/PaperInformation/StyleFiles) \| [ICML](https://icml.cc/Conferences/2025/AuthorInstructions) \| [ICLR](https://iclr.cc/Conferences/2026/AuthorGui
PIT|**Starting a new research paper** from an existing codebase or idea
PIT|**Designing and running experiments** to support paper claims
PIT|**Writing or revising** any section of a research paper
PIT|**Preparing for submission** to a specific conference or workshop
PIT|**Responding to reviews** with additional experiments or revisions
PIT|**Converting** a paper between conference formats
PIT|**Writing non-empirical papers** — theory, survey, benchmark, or position papers (see [Paper Types Beyond Empirical ML](#paper-types-beyond-empirical-ml))
PIT|**Designing human evaluations** for NLP, HCI, or alignment research
PIT|**Preparing post-acceptance deliverables** — posters, talks, code releases
PIT|**Be proactive.** Deliver complete drafts, not questions. Scientists are busy — produce something concrete they can react to, then iterate.
PIT|**Never hallucinate citations.** AI-generated citations have ~40% error rate. Always fetch programmatically. Mark unverifiable citations as `[CITATION NEEDED]`.
PIT|**Paper is a story, not a collection of experiments.** Every paper needs one clear contribution stated in a single sentence. If you can't do that, the paper isn't ready.
PIT|**Experiments serve claims.** Every experiment must explicitly state which claim it supports. Never run experiments that don't connect to the paper's narrative.
PIT|**Commit early, commit often.** Every completed experiment batch, every paper draft update — commit with descriptive messages. Git log is the experiment history.
PIT|Default: Be proactive. Draft first, ask with the draft.**
PIT|Block for input only when**: target venue unclear, multiple contradictory framings, results seem incomplete, explicit request to review first.
PIT|Goal**: Establish the workspace, understand existing work, identify the contribution.
PIT|`README.md` — project overview and claims
PIT|`results/`, `outputs/`, `experiments/` — existing findings
PIT|`configs/` — experimental settings
PIT|`.bib` files — existing citations
PIT|Draft documents or notes
PIT|Git discipline**: Every completed experiment batch gets committed with a descriptive message. Example:
PIT|**The What**: What is the single thing this paper contributes?
PIT|**The Why**: What evidence supports it?
PIT|**The So What**: Why should readers care?
PIT|[ ] Define one-sentence contribution
PIT|[ ] Literature review (related work + baselines)
PIT|[ ] Design core experiments
PIT|[ ] Run experiments
PIT|[ ] Analyze results
PIT|[ ] Write first draft
PIT|[ ] Self-review (simulate reviewers)
PIT|[ ] Revise based on review
PIT|[ ] Submission prep
PIT|[ ] API costs: (model price per token) × (estimated tokens per run) × (number of runs)
PIT|[ ] GPU hours: (time per experiment) × (number of experiments) × (number of seeds)
PIT|[ ] Human evaluation costs: (annotators) × (hours) × (hourly rate)
PIT|[ ] Total budget ceiling and contingency (add 30-50% for reruns)
PIT|When budget is tight**: Run pilot experiments (1-2 seeds, subset of tasks) before committing to full sweeps. Use cheaper models for debugging pipelines, then switch to target models for final runs.
PIT|Section ownership**: Assign each section to one primary author. Others comment but don't edit directly. Prevents merge conflicts and style inconsistency.
PIT|[ ] Agree on section ownership (who writes what)
PIT|[ ] Set up shared workspace (Overleaf or git repo)
PIT|[ ] Establish notation conventions (before anyone writes)
PIT|[ ] Schedule internal review rounds (not just at the end)
PIT|[ ] Designate one person for final formatting pass
PIT|[ ] Agree on figure style (colors, fonts, sizes) before creating figures
PIT|LaTeX conventions to agree on early**:
PIT|`\method{}` macro for consistent method naming
PIT|Citation style: `\citet{}` vs `\citep{}` usage
PIT|Math notation: lowercase bold for vectors, uppercase bold for matrices, etc.
PIT|British vs American spelling
PIT|Goal**: Find related work, identify baselines, gather citations.
PIT|Load the `arxiv` skill** for structured paper discovery: `skill_view("arxiv")`. It provides arXiv REST API search, Semantic Scholar citation graphs, author profiles, and BibTeX generation.
PIT|"[main technique] + [application domain]"
PIT|"[baseline method] comparison"
PIT|"[problem name] state-of-the-art"
PIT|Author names from existing citations
PIT|Recommended**: Install **Exa MCP** for real-time academic search:
PIT|When to stop**: If a round returns >80% papers already in your collection, the search is saturated. Typically 2-3 rounds suffice. For survey papers, expect 4-5 rounds.
PIT|For agent-based workflows**: Delegate each round's queries in parallel via `delegate_task`. Collect results, deduplicate, then generate the next round's queries from the combined learnings.
PIT|NEVER generate BibTeX from memory. ALWAYS fetch programmatically.**
PIT|SEARCH → Query Semantic Scholar or Exa MCP with specific keywords
PIT|VERIFY → Confirm paper exists in 2+ sources (Semantic Scholar + arXiv/CrossRef)
PIT|RETRIEVE → Get BibTeX via DOI content negotiation (programmatically, not from memory)
PIT|VALIDATE → Confirm the claim you're citing actually appears in the paper
PIT|ADD → Add verified BibTeX to bibliography
PIT|Always tell the scientist**: "I've marked [X] citations as placeholders that need verification."
PIT|Good**: "One line of work uses X's assumption [refs] whereas we use Y's assumption because..."
PIT|Bad**: "Smith et al. introduced X. Jones et al. introduced Y. We combine both."
PIT|Goal**: Design experiments that directly support paper claims. Every experiment must answer a specific question.
PIT|Rule**: If an experiment doesn't map to a claim, don't run it.
PIT|**Naive baseline**: Simplest possible approach
PIT|**Strong baseline**: Best known existing method
PIT|**Ablation baselines**: Your method minus one component
PIT|**Compute-matched baselines**: Same compute budget, different allocation
PIT|**Metrics**: What you're measuring, direction symbols (higher/lower better)
PIT|**Aggregation**: How results are combined across runs/tasks
PIT|**Statistical tests**: What tests will establish significance
PIT|**Sample sizes**: How many runs/problems/tasks
PIT|Incremental saving** — save results after each step for crash recovery:
PIT|Artifact preservation** — save all intermediate outputs:
PIT|Separation of concerns** — keep generation, evaluation, and visualization separate:
PIT|When human evaluation is needed:**
PIT|Automated metrics don't capture what you care about (fluency, helpfulness, safety)
PIT|Your contribution is about human-facing qualities (readability, preference, trust)
PIT|Reviewers at NLP venues (ACL, EMNLP) expect it for generation tasks
PIT|Key design decisions:**
PIT|Annotation guideline checklist:**
PIT|[ ] Clear task description with examples (good AND bad)
PIT|[ ] Decision criteria for ambiguous cases
PIT|[ ] At least 2 worked examples per category
PIT|[ ] Attention checks / gold standard items (10-15% of total)
PIT|[ ] Qualification task or screening round
PIT|[ ] Estimated time per item and fair compensation (>= local minimum wage)
PIT|[ ] IRB/ethics review if required by your institution
PIT|Reporting requirements** (reviewers check all of these):
PIT|Number of annotators and their qualifications
PIT|Inter-annotator agreement with specific metric and value
PIT|Compensation details (amount, estimated hourly rate)
PIT|Annotation interface description or screenshot (appendix)
PIT|Total annotation time
PIT|Goal**: Run experiments reliably, monitor progress, recover from failures.
PIT|Parallel execution**: Run independent experiments simultaneously, but be aware of API rate limits. 4+ concurrent experiments on the same API will slow each down.
PIT|Check if process is still running: ps aux \| grep <pattern>
PIT|Read last 30 lines of log: tail -30 <logfile>
PIT|Check for completed results: ls <result_dir>
PIT|If results exist, read and report: cat <result_file>
PIT|If all done, commit: git add -A && git commit -m "<descriptive message>" && git push
PIT|Report in structured format (tables with key metrics)
PIT|Answer the key analytical question for this experiment
PIT|Silent mode**: If nothing has changed since the last check, respond with `[SILENT]` to suppress notification to the user. Only report when there's news.
PIT|Key**: Scripts should always check for existing results and skip completed work. This makes re-runs safe and efficient.
PIT|Why a journal, not just git?** Git tracks file changes. The journal tracks the reasoning: why you tried X, what you learned, and what that implies for the next experiment. When writing the paper, this
PIT|Selecting the best path**: When the journal shows a branching tree (exp_001 → exp_002a, exp_002b, exp_003), identify the path that best supports the paper's claims. Document dead-end branches in the a
PIT|Snapshot code per experiment**: Copy the experiment script after each run:
PIT|Goal**: Extract findings, compute statistics, identify the story.
PIT|Load all result files from a batch
PIT|Compute per-task and aggregate metrics
PIT|Generate summary tables
PIT|**Error bars**: Standard deviation or standard error, specify which
PIT|**Confidence intervals**: 95% CI for key results
PIT|**Pairwise tests**: McNemar's test for comparing two methods
PIT|**Effect sizes**: Cohen's d or h for practical significance
PIT|**What is the main finding?** State it in one sentence.
PIT|**What surprised you?** Unexpected results often make the best papers.
PIT|**What failed?** Failed experiments can be the most informative. Honest reporting of failures strengthens the paper.
PIT|**What follow-up experiments are needed?** Results often raise new questions.
PIT|How to write a negative results paper:**
PIT|Lead with what the community believes and why it matters to test it
PIT|Describe your rigorous methodology (must be airtight — reviewers will scrutinize harder)
PIT|Present the null result clearly with statistical evidence
PIT|Analyze **why** the expected result didn't materialize
PIT|Discuss implications for the field
PIT|Venues that explicitly welcome negative results**: NeurIPS (Datasets & Benchmarks track), TMLR, ML Reproducibility Challenge, workshops at major conferences. Some workshops specifically call for negat
PIT|Figures**:
PIT|Use vector graphics (PDF) for all plots: `plt.savefig('fig.pdf')`
PIT|Colorblind-safe palettes (Okabe-Ito or Paul Tol)
PIT|Self-contained captions — reader should understand without main text
PIT|No title inside figure — the caption serves this function
PIT|Tables**:
PIT|Use `booktabs` LaTeX package
PIT|Bold best value per metric
PIT|Include direction symbols (higher/lower better)
PIT|Consistent decimal precision
PIT|Create `experiment_log.md`** with the following structure:
PIT|**Claim tested**: [Which paper claim this supports]
PIT|**Setup**: [Model, dataset, config, number of runs]
PIT|**Key result**: [One sentence with the number]
PIT|**Result files**: results/exp1/final_info.json
PIT|**Figures generated**: figures/exp1_comparison.pdf
PIT|**Surprising findings**: [Anything unexpected]
PIT|[What was tried, why it failed, what it tells us]
PIT|[Anything the results raised that the paper should address]
PIT|Why this matters**: When drafting, the agent (or a delegated sub-agent) can load `experiment_log.md` alongside the LaTeX template and produce a first draft grounded in actual results. Without this bri
PIT|Git discipline**: Commit this log alongside the results it describes.
PIT|Core insight**: Autoreason's value depends on the gap between a model's generation capability and its self-evaluation capability.
PIT|**Critic** → finds problems in incumbent A (no fixes)
PIT|**Author B** → revises A based on critique
PIT|**Synthesizer** → merges A and B (randomized labels)
PIT|**Judge Panel** → 3 blind CoT judges rank A, B, AB via Borda count
PIT|**Convergence** → A wins k=2 consecutive passes → done
PIT|Key parameters:**
PIT|k=2 convergence (k=1 premature, k=3 too expensive, no quality gain)
PIT|CoT judges always (3x faster convergence)
PIT|Temperature 0.8 authors, 0.3 judges
PIT|Conservative tiebreak: incumbent wins ties
PIT|Every role is a fresh agent with no shared context
PIT|**Provide ground truth to the critic**: actual experimental data, result JSONs, statistical outputs. Without this, models hallucinate fabricated ablation studies and fake confidence intervals.
PIT|**Use 3 working judges minimum**: A broken judge parser doesn't add noise — it prevents equilibrium entirely.
PIT|**Scope constrain the revision**: "Address these specific weaknesses" not "improve the paper."
PIT|Goal**: Write a complete, publication-ready paper.
PIT|What to load into context per drafting task:**
PIT|Principles:**
PIT|**`experiment_log.md` is the primary context bridge** — it summarizes everything needed for writing without loading raw data files (see Step 4.6)
PIT|**Load one section's context at a time** when delegating. A sub-agent drafting Methods doesn't need the literature review notes.
PIT|**Summarize, don't include raw files.** For a 200-line result JSON, load a 10-line summary table. For a 50-page related paper, load the 5-sentence abstract + your 2-line note about its relevance.
PIT|**For very large projects**: Create a `context/` directory with pre-compressed summaries:
PIT|The single most critical insight**: Your paper is not a collection of experiments — it's a story with one clear contribution supported by evidence.
PIT|Three Pillars (must be crystal clear by end of introduction):**
PIT|If you cannot state your contribution in one sentence, you don't yet have a paper.**
PIT|For deeper dives into any of these, see:**
PIT|[references/writing-guide.md](references/writing-guide.md) — Full explanations with examples
PIT|[references/sources.md](references/sources.md) — Complete bibliography
PIT|The abstract
PIT|The introduction
PIT|The figures
PIT|Everything else combined
PIT|Why?** Most reviewers form judgments before reaching your methods. Readers encounter your paper as: title → abstract → introduction → figures → maybe the rest.
PIT|[ ] Step 1: Define the one-sentence contribution
PIT|[ ] Step 2: Draft Figure 1 (core idea or most compelling result)
PIT|[ ] Step 3: Draft abstract (5-sentence formula)
PIT|[ ] Step 4: Draft introduction (1-1.5 pages max)
PIT|[ ] Step 5: Draft methods
PIT|[ ] Step 6: Draft experiments & results
PIT|[ ] Step 7: Draft related work
PIT|[ ] Step 8: Draft conclusion & discussion
PIT|[ ] Step 9: Draft limitations (REQUIRED by all venues)
PIT|[ ] Step 10: Plan appendix (proofs, extra experiments, details)
PIT|[ ] Step 11: Complete paper checklist
PIT|[ ] Step 12: Final review
PIT|Pass 1 — Write + immediate refine per section:**
PIT|Pass 2 — Global refinement with full-paper context:**
PIT|Does it fit with the rest of the paper? Are there redundancies with other sections?
PIT|Is terminology consistent with Introduction and Methods?
PIT|Can anything be cut without weakening the message?
PIT|Does the narrative flow from the previous section and into the next?
PIT|[ ] No unenclosed math symbols ($ signs balanced)
PIT|[ ] Only reference figures/tables that exist (\ref matches \label)
PIT|[ ] No fabricated citations (\cite matches entries in .bib)
PIT|[ ] Every \begin{env} has matching \end{env} (especially figure, table, algorithm)
PIT|[ ] No HTML contamination (</end{figure}> instead of \end{figure})
PIT|[ ] No unescaped underscores outside math mode (use \_ in text)
PIT|[ ] No duplicate \label definitions
PIT|[ ] No duplicate section headers
PIT|[ ] Numbers in text match actual experimental results
PIT|[ ] All figures have captions and labels
PIT|[ ] No overly long lines that cause overfull hbox warnings
PIT|Good titles**:
PIT|State the contribution or finding: "Autoreason: When Iterative LLM Refinement Works and Why It Fails"
PIT|Highlight a surprising result: "Scaling Data-Constrained Language Models" (implies you can)
PIT|Name the method + what it does: "DPO: Direct Preference Optimization of Language Models"
PIT|Bad titles**:
PIT|Too generic: "An Approach to Improving Language Model Outputs"
PIT|Too long: anything over ~15 words
PIT|Jargon-only: "Asymptotic Convergence of Iterative Stochastic Policy Refinement" (who is this for?)
PIT|Rules**:
PIT|Include your method name if you have one (for citability)
PIT|Include 1-2 keywords reviewers will search for
PIT|Avoid colons unless both halves carry meaning
PIT|Test: would a reviewer know the domain and contribution from the title alone?
PIT|What you achieved: "We introduce...", "We prove...", "We demonstrate..."
PIT|Why this is hard and important
PIT|How you do it (with specialist keywords for discoverability)
PIT|What evidence you have
PIT|Your most remarkable number/result
PIT|Delete** generic openings like "Large language models have achieved remarkable success..."
PIT|Rules**: Figure 1 must be understandable without reading any text. The caption alone should communicate the core idea. Use color purposefully — don't just decorate.
PIT|Clear problem statement
PIT|Brief approach overview
PIT|2-4 bullet contribution list (max 1-2 lines each in two-column format)
PIT|Methods should start by page 2-3
PIT|Conceptual outline or pseudocode
PIT|All hyperparameters listed
PIT|Architectural details sufficient for reproduction
PIT|Present final design decisions; ablations go in experiments
PIT|**What claim it supports**
PIT|How it connects to main contribution
PIT|What to observe: "the blue line shows X, which demonstrates Y"
PIT|Error bars with methodology (std dev vs std error)
PIT|Hyperparameter search ranges
PIT|Compute infrastructure (GPU type, total hours)
PIT|Seed-setting methods
PIT|Reviewers are instructed not to penalize honest limitation acknowledgment
PIT|Pre-empt criticisms by identifying weaknesses first
PIT|Explain why limitations don't undermine core claims
PIT|Conclusion** (required, 0.5-1 page):
PIT|Restate the contribution in one sentence (different wording from abstract)
PIT|Summarize key findings (2-3 sentences, not a list)
PIT|Implications: what does this mean for the field?
PIT|Future work: 2-3 concrete next steps (not vague "we leave X for future work")
PIT|Discussion** (optional, sometimes combined with conclusion):
PIT|Broader implications beyond immediate results
PIT|Connections to other subfields
PIT|Honest assessment of when the method does and doesn't work
PIT|Practical deployment considerations
PIT|Do NOT** introduce new results or claims in the conclusion.
PIT|Rules**:
PIT|The main paper must be self-contained — reviewers are not required to read appendices
PIT|Never put critical evidence only in the appendix
PIT|Cross-reference: "Full results in Table 5 (Appendix B)" not just "see appendix"
PIT|Use `\appendix` command, then `\section{A: Proofs}` etc.
PIT|Do NOT**: reduce font size, change margins, remove required sections (limitations, broader impact), or use `\small`/`\footnotesize` for main text.
PIT|What to include:**
PIT|Writing the statement:**
PIT|Common mistakes:**
PIT|Writing "we foresee no negative impacts" (almost never true — reviewers distrust this)
PIT|Being vague: "this could be misused" without specifying how
PIT|Ignoring compute costs for large-scale work
PIT|Forgetting to disclose LLM use at venues that require it
PIT|Compute carbon footprint** (for training-heavy papers):
PIT|Datasheets for Datasets** (Gebru et al., 2021) — include in appendix:
PIT|Motivation: Why was this dataset created? What task does it support?
PIT|Composition: What are the instances? How many? What data types?
PIT|Collection: How was data collected? What was the source?
PIT|Preprocessing: What cleaning/filtering was applied?
PIT|Distribution: How is the dataset distributed? Under what license?
PIT|Maintenance: Who maintains it? How to report issues?
PIT|Ethical considerations: Contains personal data? Consent obtained?
PIT|Model Cards** (Mitchell et al., 2019) — include in appendix for model releases:
PIT|Model details: Architecture, training data, training procedure
PIT|Intended use: Primary use cases, out-of-scope uses
PIT|Metrics: Evaluation metrics and results on benchmarks
PIT|Ethical considerations: Known biases, fairness evaluations
PIT|Limitations: Known failure modes, domains where model underperforms
PIT|Sentence-level clarity (Gopen & Swan's 7 Principles):**
PIT|Word choice (Lipton, Steinhardt):**
PIT|Be specific: "accuracy" not "performance"
PIT|Eliminate hedging: drop "may" unless genuinely uncertain
PIT|Consistent terminology throughout
PIT|Avoid incremental vocabulary: "develop", not "combine"
PIT|Full writing guide with examples**: See [references/writing-guide.md](references/writing-guide.md)
PIT|Always copy the entire template directory first, then write within it.**
PIT|[ ] Step 1: Copy entire template directory to new project
PIT|[ ] Step 2: Verify template compiles as-is (before any changes)
PIT|[ ] Step 3: Read the template's example content to understand structure
PIT|[ ] Step 4: Replace example content section by section
PIT|[ ] Step 5: Use template macros (check preamble for \newcommand definitions)
PIT|[ ] Step 6: Clean up template artifacts only at the end
PIT|Step 1: Copy the Full Template**
PIT|Step 2: Verify Template Compiles First**
PIT|Step 3: Keep Template Content as Reference**
PIT|Step 4: Replace Content Section by Section**
PIT|Step 5: Use Template Macros**
PIT|Universal**: Double-blind, references don't count, appendices unlimited, LaTeX required.
PIT|Tables** — use `booktabs` for professional formatting:
PIT|Bold best value per metric
PIT|Include direction symbols ($\uparrow$ higher better, $\downarrow$ lower better)
PIT|Right-align numerical columns
PIT|Consistent decimal precision
PIT|Figures**:
PIT|**Vector graphics** (PDF, EPS) for all plots and diagrams — `plt.savefig('fig.pdf')`
PIT|**Raster** (PNG 600 DPI) only for photographs
PIT|**Colorblind-safe palettes** (Okabe-Ito or Paul Tol)
PIT|Verify **grayscale readability** (8% of men have color vision deficiency)
PIT|**No title inside figure** — the caption serves this function
PIT|**Self-contained captions** — reader should understand without main text
PIT|Notes:**
PIT|`microtype` is the single highest-impact package for visual quality. It adjusts character spacing at a sub-pixel level. Always include it.
PIT|`siunitx` handles decimal alignment in tables via the `S` column type — eliminates manual spacing.
PIT|`cleveref` must be loaded **after** `hyperref`. Most conference .sty files load hyperref, so put cleveref last.
PIT|Check if the conference template already loads any of these (especially `algorithm`, `amsmath`, `graphicx`). Don't double-load.
PIT|Pipeline/Flow Diagram** (most common in ML papers):
PIT|Comparison/Matrix Diagram** (for showing method variants):
PIT|Iterative Loop Diagram** (for methods with feedback):
PIT|Standard figure sizes** (two-column format):
PIT|Single column: `figsize=(3.5, 2.5)` — fits in one column
PIT|Double column: `figsize=(7.0, 3.0)` — spans both columns
PIT|Square: `figsize=(3.5, 3.5)` — for heatmaps, confusion matrices
PIT|Goal**: Simulate the review process before submission. Catch weaknesses early.
PIT|Step 1: Generate N independent reviews** (N=3-5)
PIT|Soundness (are claims well-supported? are baselines fair and strong?)
PIT|Clarity (is the paper well-written? could an expert reproduce it?)
PIT|Significance (does this matter to the community?)
PIT|Originality (new insights, not just incremental combination?)
PIT|Step 2: Meta-review (Area Chair aggregation)**
PIT|Identify consensus strengths and weaknesses across reviewers
PIT|Resolve disagreements by examining the paper directly
PIT|Produce a meta-review that represents the aggregate judgment
PIT|Use AVERAGED numerical scores across all reviews
PIT|Step 3: Reflection loop** (optional, 2-3 rounds)
PIT|Model selection for reviewing**: Reviewing is best done with the strongest available model, even if you wrote the paper with a cheaper one. The reviewer model should be chosen independently from the w
PIT|Few-shot calibration**: If available, include 1-2 real published reviews from the target venue as examples. This dramatically improves score calibration. See [references/reviewer-guidelines.md](refere
PIT|Figure quality: Are plots readable? Labels legible? Colors distinguishable?
PIT|Figure-caption alignment: Does each caption accurately describe its figure?
PIT|Layout issues: Orphaned section headers, awkward page breaks, figures far from their references
PIT|Table formatting: Aligned columns, consistent decimal precision, bold for best results
PIT|Visual consistency: Same color scheme across all figures, consistent font sizes
PIT|Grayscale readability: Would the figures be understandable if printed in B&W?
PIT|Extract every factual claim from the paper (numbers, comparisons, trends)
PIT|For each claim, trace it to the specific experiment/result that supports it
PIT|Verify the number in the paper matches the actual result file
PIT|Flag any claim without a traceable source as [VERIFY]
PIT|Identify the specific section(s) affected
PIT|Draft the fix
PIT|Verify the fix doesn't break other claims
PIT|Update the paper
PIT|Re-check against the reviewer's concern
PIT|Format**: Point-by-point. For each reviewer concern:
PIT|Rules**:
PIT|Address every concern — reviewers notice if you skip one
PIT|Lead with the strongest responses
PIT|Be concise and direct — reviewers read dozens of rebuttals
PIT|Include new results if you ran experiments during the rebuttal period
PIT|Never be defensive or dismissive, even of weak criticisms
PIT|Use `latexdiff` to generate a marked-up PDF showing changes (see Professional LaTeX Tooling section)
PIT|Thank reviewers for specific, actionable feedback (not generic praise)
PIT|What NOT to do**: "We respectfully disagree" without evidence. "This is out of scope" without explanation. Ignoring a weakness by only responding to strengths.
PIT|Goal**: Final checks, formatting, and submission.
PIT|NeurIPS 16-item paper checklist
PIT|ICML broader impact + reproducibility
PIT|ICLR LLM disclosure policy
PIT|ACL mandatory limitations section
PIT|Universal pre-submission checklist
PIT|[ ] No author names or affiliations anywhere in the PDF
PIT|[ ] No acknowledgments section (add after acceptance)
PIT|[ ] Self-citations written in third person: "Smith et al. [1] showed..." not "We previously showed [1]..."
PIT|[ ] No GitHub/GitLab URLs pointing to your personal repos
PIT|[ ] Use Anonymous GitHub (https://anonymous.4open.science/) for code links
PIT|[ ] No institutional logos or identifiers in figures
PIT|[ ] No file metadata containing author names (check PDF properties)
PIT|[ ] No "our previous work" or "in our earlier paper" phrasing
PIT|[ ] Dataset names don't reveal institution (rename if needed)
PIT|[ ] Supplementary materials don't contain identifying information
PIT|Common mistakes**: Git commit messages visible in supplementary code, watermarked figures from institutional tools, acknowledgments left in from a previous draft, arXiv preprint posted before anonymit
PIT|[ ] Page limit respected (excluding references and appendix)
PIT|[ ] All figures are vector (PDF) or high-res raster (600 DPI PNG)
PIT|[ ] All figures readable in grayscale
PIT|[ ] All tables use booktabs
PIT|[ ] References compile correctly (no "?" in citations)
PIT|[ ] No overfull hboxes in critical areas
PIT|[ ] Appendix clearly labeled and separated
PIT|[ ] Required sections present (limitations, broader impact, etc.)
PIT|If compilation fails**: Parse the `.log` file for the first error. Common fixes:
PIT|"Undefined control sequence" → missing package or typo in command name
PIT|"Missing $ inserted" → math symbol outside math mode
PIT|"File not found" → wrong figure path or missing .sty file
PIT|"Citation undefined" → .bib entry missing or bibtex not run
PIT|After rejection**: Address reviewer concerns in the new version, but don't include a "changes" section or reference the previous submission (blind review).
PIT|[ ] De-anonymize: add author names, affiliations, email addresses
PIT|[ ] Add Acknowledgments section (funding, compute grants, helpful reviewers)
PIT|[ ] Add public code/data URL (real GitHub, not anonymous)
PIT|[ ] Address any mandatory revisions from meta-reviewer
PIT|[ ] Switch template to camera-ready mode (if applicable — e.g., AAAI \anon → \camera)
PIT|[ ] Add copyright notice if required by venue
PIT|[ ] Update any "anonymous" placeholders in text
PIT|[ ] Verify final PDF compiles cleanly
PIT|[ ] Check page limit for camera-ready (sometimes differs from submission)
PIT|[ ] Upload supplementary materials (code, data, appendix) to venue portal
PIT|Timing decision tree:**
PIT|arXiv category selection** (ML/AI papers):
PIT|List primary + 1-2 cross-listed categories.** More categories = more visibility, but only cross-list where genuinely relevant.
PIT|Versioning strategy:**
PIT|**v1**: Initial submission (matches conference submission)
PIT|**v2**: Post-acceptance with camera-ready corrections (add "accepted at [Venue]" to abstract)
PIT|Don't post v2 during the review period with changes that clearly respond to reviewer feedback
PIT|Repository structure:**
PIT|README template for research code:**
PIT|Pre-release checklist:**
PIT|[ ] Code runs from a clean clone (test on fresh machine or Docker)
PIT|[ ] All dependencies pinned to specific versions
PIT|[ ] No hardcoded absolute paths
PIT|[ ] No API keys, credentials, or personal data in repo
PIT|[ ] README covers setup, reproduction, and citation
PIT|[ ] LICENSE file present (MIT or Apache 2.0 for max reuse)
PIT|[ ] Results are reproducible within expected variance
PIT|[ ] .gitignore excludes data files, checkpoints, logs
PIT|Anonymous code for submission** (before acceptance):
PIT|Goal**: Maximize the impact of your accepted paper through presentation materials and community engagement.
PIT|Tools**: LaTeX (`beamerposter` package), PowerPoint/Keynote, Figma, Canva.
PIT|Production**: Order 2+ weeks before the conference. Fabric posters are lighter for travel. Many conferences now support virtual/digital posters too.
PIT|Slide design rules:**
PIT|One idea per slide
PIT|Minimize text — speak the details, don't project them
PIT|Animate key figures to build understanding step-by-step
PIT|Include a "takeaway" slide at the end (single sentence contribution)
PIT|Prepare backup slides for anticipated questions
PIT|**Twitter/X thread**: 5-8 tweets. Lead with the result, not the method. Include Figure 1 and key result figure.
PIT|**Blog post**: 800-1500 words. Written for ML practitioners, not reviewers. Skip formalism, emphasize intuition and practical implications.
PIT|**Project page**: HTML page with abstract, figures, demo, code link, BibTeX. Use GitHub Pages.
PIT|Timing**: Post within 1-2 days of paper appearing on proceedings or arXiv camera-ready.
PIT|When to target a workshop:**
PIT|Early-stage idea you want feedback on before a full paper
PIT|Negative result that doesn't justify 8+ pages
PIT|Position piece or opinion on a timely topic
PIT|Replication study or reproducibility report
PIT|Short paper strategy**: Pick ONE claim and support it thoroughly. Don't try to compress a long paper into 4 pages — write a different, more focused paper.
PIT|Structure**: Introduction → Preliminaries (definitions, notation) → Main Results (theorems) → Proof Sketches → Discussion → Full Proofs (appendix)
PIT|Key differences from empirical papers:**
PIT|Contribution is a theorem, bound, or impossibility result — not experimental numbers
PIT|Methods section replaced by "Preliminaries" and "Main Results"
PIT|Proofs are the evidence, not experiments (though empirical validation of theory is welcome)
PIT|Proof sketches in main text, full proofs in appendix is standard practice
PIT|Experimental section is optional but strengthens the paper if it validates theoretical predictions
PIT|Proof writing principles:**
PIT|State theorems formally with all assumptions explicit
PIT|Provide intuition before formal proof ("The key insight is...")
PIT|Proof sketches should convey the main idea in 0.5-1 page
PIT|Use `\begin{proof}...\end{proof}` environments
PIT|Number assumptions and reference them in theorems: "Under Assumptions 1-3, ..."
PIT|Structure**: Introduction → Taxonomy / Organization → Detailed Coverage → Open Problems → Conclusion
PIT|Key differences:**
PIT|Contribution is the organization, synthesis, and identification of open problems — not new methods
PIT|Must be comprehensive within scope (reviewers will check for missing references)
PIT|Requires a clear taxonomy or organizational framework
PIT|Value comes from connections between works that individual papers don't make
PIT|Best venues: TMLR (survey track), JMLR, Foundations and Trends in ML, ACM Computing Surveys
PIT|Structure**: Introduction → Task Definition → Dataset Construction → Baseline Evaluation → Analysis → Intended Use & Limitations
PIT|Key differences:**
PIT|Contribution is the benchmark itself — it must fill a genuine evaluation gap
PIT|Dataset documentation is mandatory, not optional (see Datasheets, Step 5.11)
PIT|Must demonstrate the benchmark is challenging (baselines don't saturate it)
PIT|Must demonstrate the benchmark measures what you claim it measures (construct validity)
PIT|Best venues: NeurIPS Datasets & Benchmarks track, ACL (resource papers), LREC-COLING
PIT|Structure**: Introduction → Background → Thesis / Argument → Supporting Evidence → Counterarguments → Implications
PIT|Key differences:**
PIT|Contribution is an argument, not a result
PIT|Must engage seriously with counterarguments
PIT|Evidence can be empirical, theoretical, or logical analysis
PIT|Best venues: ICML (position track), workshops, TMLR
PIT|This skill supersedes `ml-paper-writing`** — it contains all of ml-paper-writing's content plus the full experiment/analysis pipeline and autoreason methodology.
PIT|Experiment monitoring** (most common):
PIT|Parallel section drafting** (using delegation):
PIT|Citation verification** (using execute_code):
PIT|`memory` tool** — persist key decisions (bounded: ~2200 chars for MEMORY.md):
PIT|`todo` tool** — track granular progress:
PIT|Session startup protocol:**
PIT|todo("list") # Check current task list
PIT|memory("read") # Recall key decisions
PIT|terminal("git log --oneline -10") # Check recent commits
PIT|terminal("ps aux \| grep python") # Check running experiments
PIT|terminal("ls results/ \| tail -20") # Check for new results
PIT|Report status to user, ask for direction
PIT|[SILENT] protocol**: When nothing has changed since the last check, respond with exactly `[SILENT]`. This suppresses notification delivery to the user. Only report when there are genuine changes worth
PIT|Deadline tracking**:
PIT|When to notify the user** (via `send_message` or direct response):
PIT|Experiment batch completed (with results table)
PIT|Unexpected finding or failure requiring decision
PIT|Draft section ready for review
PIT|Deadline approaching with incomplete tasks
PIT|When NOT to notify:**
PIT|Experiment still running, no new results → `[SILENT]`
PIT|Routine monitoring with no changes → `[SILENT]`
PIT|Intermediate steps that don't need attention
PIT|Report format** — always include structured data:
PIT|Do NOT ask about** (be proactive, make a choice, flag it):
PIT|Word choice, section ordering
PIT|Which specific results to highlight
PIT|Citation completeness (draft with what you find, note gaps)
PIT|Scoring (NeurIPS 6-point scale):**
PIT|6: Strong Accept — groundbreaking, flawless
PIT|5: Accept — technically solid, high impact
PIT|4: Borderline Accept — solid, limited evaluation
PIT|3: Borderline Reject — weaknesses outweigh
PIT|2: Reject — technical flaws
PIT|1: Strong Reject — known results or ethics issues
PIT|Writing Philosophy:**
PIT|[Neel Nanda: How to Write ML Papers](https://www.alignmentforum.org/posts/eJGptPbbFPZGLpjsp/highly-opinionated-advice-on-how-to-write-ml-papers)
